[[College Basketball on ESPN|ESPN]]\n| [[Dan Shulman]]\n| [[Jay Bilas]]\n|-\n| December 29, 2017\n| [[College Basketball on CBS|CBS]]\n| [[Spero Dedes]]\n| [[Bill Raftery]]\n|-\n| December 29, 2018\n| [[College Basketball on ESPN|ESPN2]]\n| [[Dan Shulman]]\n| [[Jay Bilas]]\n|-\n| December 28, 2019\n| [[College Basketball on CBS|CBS]]\n| [[Brad Nessler]]\n| [[Bill Raftery]]\n|}\n\n===Football===\n{{Main|Governor's Cup (Kentucky)}}\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2017}}\nThe football rivalry between Kentucky and Louisville started one year earlier than the basketball rivalry but also had a long dormant period.  Kentucky and Louisville first played each other in football in 1912. Kentucky dominated six meetings between the teams from 1912 until 1924, holding Louisville scoreless in all six games, after which the teams stopped playing. In 1994, with former Kentucky player Howard Schnellenberger coaching Louisville, the series was revived after a 70-year dormancy.  Kentucky leads the series currently 17\u201315 but Louisville leads the Governors Cup series 15-11.\n\nFrom 1994 to 2006 the annual matchup was the first game of the season for Kentucky and was the first game for all but two of those years for Louisville.  In 2007 the game was moved to the third game of the season when played in Lexington but remained the first game when played in Louisville. Starting in 2014, which marked Louisville's inaugural season in the Atlantic Coast Conference, the Governor's Cup became the last game of the regular season for both teams to coincide with several other ACC-SEC same-state rivalries.\n\nThe 2019 game was won by Kentucky 45-13.  Kentucky wide receiver Lynn Bowden Jr. was named MVP of the showdown.\n\n== Other sports ==\n\n* '''Women's basketball''': Kentucky leads the series 34\u201320 as of the 2017\u201318 season. Most recently, no. 3 Louisville beat Kentucky 87-63 in Lexington on December 17, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukathletics.com/news/2017/12/17/womens-basketball-kentucky-louisville-postgame-notes.aspx?path=wbball|title=Kentucky-Louisville Postgame Notes|publisher=University of Kentucky Athletics|accessdate=January 29, 2018|date=December 17, 2017}}</ref> Kentucky entered that game having won five of the past six meetings with Louisville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukathletics.com/news/2017/12/15/womens-basketball-kentucky-hosts-no-3-4-louisville-sunday-in-memorial-coliseum.aspx?path=wbball|title=Kentucky Hosts No. 3/4 Louisville Sunday in Memorial Coliseum|publisher=University of Kentucky|accessdate=January 29, 2018|date=December 15, 2017}}</ref> The series dates back to the 1911\u201312 season, long before Kentucky and Louisville's programs became varsity in 1974\u201375, from which the series has been continuously active.<ref name=\"WBB series\">{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/ukathletics.com/documents/2017/11/3/2017_18_WBB_Media_Guide_Complete_FNL.pdf|title=Scores vs. All Opponents|page=153|work=Believe in Blue: 2017-18 Women's Basketball Media Guide|publisher=University of Kentucky|year=2017}}</ref>\n* '''Women's volleyball''': Most recently winning 3-0 in Lexington, Kentucky leads the series 30\u201325 as of 2018 in a series that initially was played every year from 1977 to 2005 except in 1981 and resumed in 2009 after a hiatus.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/ukathletics.com/documents/2017/8/23/Online_MEdia_GUide.pdf|pages=62-63|title=Kentucky Volleyball 2017 Media Guide|publisher=University of Kentucky|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukathletics.com/news/2017/9/15/volleyball-no-12-kentucky-wins-fifth-straight-over-louisville.aspx|title=No. 12 Kentucky Wins Fifth Straight Over Louisville|author=Moore, Deb|date=September 15, 2017|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''Men's soccer''': The two men's soccer programs have met 31 times. Kentucky leads 15\u201314\u20135. The last meeting between the two was on September 3, 2019 which ended in a 3-0 Louisville win.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wall|first1=Garrett|title=Cardinals Shut Out No. 9 Wildcats 3-0|url=http://gocards.com/news/2019/9/3/mens-soccer-cardinals-shut-out-no-9-wildcats-3-0.aspx|website=gocards.com|publisher=[[Louisville Cardinals]]|accessdate=January 21, 2018|date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Baseball''': As of 2018, Kentucky leads the series 71\u201345\u20131 in a series dating back to 1925.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/ukathletics.com/documents/2017/8/9/2017_media_guide.pdf|title=Kentucky vs. all opponents|work=2017 Kentucky Baseball Media Guide|publisher=University of Kentucky|year=2017|page=108}}</ref><ref name=\"2017 baseball\">http://ukathletics.com/schedule.aspx?schedule=37</reF> In 2017, Louisville won the season series 3\u20131, including a sweep of Kentucky in the [[2017_NCAA_Division_I_Baseball_Tournament#Louisville_Super_Regional|NCAA Tournament Louisville Super Regional]].<ref name=\"2017 baseball\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kentucky Wildcats]]\n* [[Louisville Cardinals]]\n* [[Governor's Cup (Kentucky)]]\n* [[The Rivalry: Red V. Blue]]\n* [[Local derby|Traditional athletic rivalries in many countries of the world]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Kentucky Wildcats women's basketball navbox}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals women's basketball navbox}}\n{{Kentucky Wildcats men's soccer navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kentucky-Louisville rivalry}}\n[[Category:Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball]]\n[[Category:Louisville Cardinals men's basketball]]\n[[Category:College basketball rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:College soccer rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:College sports rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sports rivalry between the Universities of Kentucky and Louisville}}\n \n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| wide                  = yes\n| name                  = Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = \n| caption               = \n| team1                 = [[Kentucky Wildcats]]\n| team1logo             = Kentucky Wildcats logo.svg\n| team2                 = [[Louisville Cardinals]]\n| team2logo             = Louisville Cardinals wordmark.svg\n| sport                 = [[college basketball|basketball]], [[college football|football]], others\n| firstmeeting          = \n| mostrecent            = \n| nextmeeting           = \n| total                 = \n| series                = \n| largestvictory        = \n| longeststreak         = \n| longestunbeatenstreak = \n| currentstreak         = \n| currentunbeatenstreak = \n| trophy                = \n| trophy series         = \n| stadiums              =  \n}}\n{{OSM Location map        \n| coord = {{coord|38.112|-85.225}}\n| zoom = 7\n| width = 295 \n| height = 250\n| caption = Locations of Kentucky and Louisville\n| mark1 = Blue pog.svg\n| label1 = Kentucky\n| mark-coord1 = {{coord|38.033333|-84.5}}\n| label-pos1 = top\n| label-color1 = black\n| mark2 = Red pog.svg\n| label2 = Louisville\n| mark-coord2 = {{coord|38.2527|-85.7585}}\n| label-pos2 = top\n| label-color2 = black\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; clear:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:88%;\"\n|+ College Comparison\n! \n! style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Kentucky Wildcats}}\" | [[University of Kentucky|{{white|Kentucky}}]]\n! style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Louisville Cardinals}}\" | [[University of Louisville|{{white|Louisville}}]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Founded\n| align=center | 1865 || align=center | 1798\n|-\n! scope=row | Type \n| align=center | [[Public university|Public]] || align=center |[[Public university|Public]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Location\n| align=center |  [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]] || align=center | [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Conference \n| align=center |  [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] || align=center | [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Students \n| align=center | 29,182 || align=center | 22,640\n|-\n! scope=row | School colors \n| align=center | {{color box|#0033A0}} {{color box|White}} || align=center | {{color box|#C9001F}} {{color box|Black}}\n|-\n! scope=row | Nickname \n| align=center |  [[Kentucky Wildcats|Wildcats]] || align=center | [[Louisville Cardinals|Cardinals]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Stadium\n| align=center | [[Kroger Field]] || align=center | [[Cardinal Stadium]]\n|-\n! scope=row | Arena\n| align=center | [[Rupp Arena]] || align=center | [[KFC Yum! Center]]\n|}\nThe '''Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry''' refers to the rivalry between the University of Kentucky Wildcats (Kentucky) and the University of Louisville Cardinals (Louisville). The Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry is one of the most passionate rivalries, especially in men's [[college basketball]]. It is considered one of the most intense rivalries in the NCAA. The intensity of the rivalry is captivated by the proximity of the two schools and the state of Kentucky's interest in college sports (no pro-affiliated sports teams play in the state of Kentucky).\n\n==Men's basketball==\n{{Main|Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Louisville Cardinals men's basketball}}\n{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| wide                  = yes\n| name                  = Kentucky\u2013Louisville men's basketball rivalry\n| image                 = \n| image_size            = \n| caption               = \n| team1                 = Kentucky Wildcats\n| team1logo             = Kentucky Wildcats logo.svg\n| team2                 = Louisville Cardinals\n| team2logo             = Louisville Cardinals wordmark.svg\n| sport                 = Basketball\n| firstmeeting          = February 15, 1913<br />Kentucky 34, Louisville 10\n| mostrecent            = December 28, 2019<br />Kentucky 78, Louisville 70\n| nextmeeting           = 2020-21 Season - Louisville, KY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://watchstadium.com/future-college-basketball-non-conference-schedules-for-2020-and-beyond-11-20-2019/|title=Future College Basketball Non-Conference Schedules for 2020 and Beyond|last=Wittry|first=Andy|website=Watch Stadium|language=en|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n| total                 = 52\n| series                = Kentucky leads, 37\u201316 Regular season and 2 NCAA\n| largestvictory        = Kentucky: 34 points (1948)<br />Louisville: 22 points (1988)\n| longeststreak         = \n| longestunbeatenstreak = \n| currentstreak         = Kentucky, 3 (2017\u2013present)\n| currentunbeatenstreak = \n| trophy                = \n| trophy series         = \n| stadiums              =  \n}}\n\nThe Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry has been ranked the 2nd best rivalry in college basketball by Bleacher Report and 3rd best rivalry in all of college sports by [[List of members of the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Basketball Hall of Fame]] contributor [[Dick Vitale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espn/dickvitale/story/_/id/7561633/dick-vitale-picks-best-rivalries-college-sports|title=Dick Vitale picks the best rivalries in college sports|work=ESPN.com}}</ref> Kentucky and Louisville first played against each other in 1913 but stopped playing each other in the 1920s, playing only twelve times between 1913 and 1983. The rivalry was generally dormant with only occasional matchups until the teams met in the [[1983 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1983 NCAA Tournament]].  Since then, the two teams have met each year in late December or early January.\n\nMuch like the [[Iron Bowl]], the Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry is all the more intense because the two schools have consistently been among the nation's elite men's basketball teams for most of the last 50 years.  Both schools are also two of the most victorious programs in [[NCAA]] men's basketball history; Kentucky is #1 on the list of all-time [[List of teams with the most victories in NCAA Division I men's college basketball|winningest program]]s in [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] Men's Basketball and Louisville #26.  Kentucky has eight national championships and Louisville three, although one was later vacated by the NCAA.  Both schools also sit in the top ten of men's basketball teams that have had athletes to be picked in the first round of the NBA draft. Kentucky has had 46 players selected in the first round, while Louisville has had 24.\n\n===History===\nThe rivalry was fueled when [[Rick Pitino]] was hired as Louisville's head men's basketball coach in 2001. He served in that same role with Kentucky from 1989 to 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/22/sports/college-basketball-louisville-hires-pitino-to-spice-a-rivalry.html|title=Louisville Hires Pitino To Spice A Rivalry|date=March 22, 2001|work=The New York Times}}</ref> In the time that Rick Pitino was the head coach at Louisville from 2001 to 2017, Kentucky has won 12 of its contests and Louisville has won 6 of its contests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/louisville/2018/12/27/louisville-kentucky-rivalry-every-basketball-game-score/2416024002/|title=See the scores of every Louisville-Kentucky basketball game in history|last=Lerner|first=Danielle|website=The Courier-Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> Kentucky leads the all-time series with Louisville 37-16, and Kentucky leads the modern series 28-13.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.bigbluehistory.net/bb/Statistics/Louisville.html|title = Kentucky's Record versus Louisville|publisher=Big Blue History|accessdate = September 16, 2007}}</ref>  In six tournament meetings as of 2014, Kentucky leads the series four games to two with their most recent win coming in the 2014 sweet sixteen 74-69. The teams met in the [[2012 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2012 Final Four]], and Kentucky defeated Louisville with a score of 69-61 en route to the national title. This was the deepest ever tournament meeting between the two schools and their first tournament meeting since 1984.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Results===\nRankings are from the [[AP Poll]] (1936\u2013present)\n\n{{sports rivalry series table\n| legend_forfeit_text = Vacated wins{{#tag:ref|Louisville has vacated all of its victories from the 2011\u201312, 2012\u201313, 2013\u201314, 2014\u201315 seasons. These 123 wins are not included in Louisville's all-time record, nor are the victories against Kentucky during this span counted in the series record between the two teams.<ref name=\"Sanctions\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/02/20/louisville-basketball-will-vacate-2013-national-championship-as-ncaa-upholds-ruling/]. [[Washington Post]], 2018-02-20.</ref>|group=\"n\"|name=\"vacation\"}}\n| format = compact| cols = 2\n| team1 = Kentucky\n| team1style = {{NCAA color cell|Kentucky Wildcats}}\n| team2 = Louisville\n| team2style = {{NCAA color cell|Louisville Cardinals}}\n| series_summary = yes\n\n| February 15, 1913 | [[Lexington, KY]] | Kentucky | 34 | Louisville | 10\n| February 7, 1914 | Lexington, KY | Kentucky | 22 | Louisville | 17\n| March 3, 1914 | [[Louisville, KY]] | Kentucky | 26 | Louisville | 13\n| January 23, 1915 | Lexington, KY | Kentucky | 18 | Louisville | 14\n| February 27, 1915 | Louisville, KY | Kentucky | 15 | Louisville | 26\n| February 12, 1916 | Lexington, KY | Kentucky | 22 | Louisville | 28\n| February 22, 1916 | Louisville, KY | Kentucky | 32 | Louisville | 24\n| January 17, 1922 | Louisville, KY | Kentucky | 38 | Louisville | 14\n| January 21, 1922 | Lexington, KY | Kentucky | 29 | Louisville | 22\n| [[1948 NCAA Basketball Tournament|March 27, 1948]]<sup>A</sup> | [[New York City|New York City, NY]] | Kentucky | 91 | Louisville | 57\n| [[1951 NCAA Basketball Tournament|March 20, 1951]]<sup>B</sup> | [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh, NC]] | No. 1 Kentucky | 79 | Louisville | 68\n| [[1959 NCAA University Division Basketball Tournament|March 13, 1959]]<sup>C</sup> | [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston, IL]] | No. 2 Kentucky | 61 | Louisville | 76\n| [[1983 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|March 26, 1983]]<sup>D</sup> | [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville, TN]] | No. 2 Louisville | 80 | No. 12 Kentucky | 68 OT\n| November 26, 1983 | Lexington, KY | No. 1 Kentucky | 65 | No. 6 Louisville | 44\n| [[1984 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|March 22, 1984]]<sup>E</sup> | Lexington, KY | No. 3 Kentucky | 72 | Louisville | 67\n| December 15, 1984 | Louisville, KY | Kentucky | 64 | No. 14 Louisville | 71\n| December 28, 1985 | Lexington, KY | No. 13 Kentucky | 69 | No. 15 Louisville | 64\n| December 27, 1986 | Louisville, KY | No. 18 Kentucky | 85 | Louisville | 51\n| December 12, 1987 | Lexington, KY | No. 1 Kentucky | 76 | Louisville | 75\n| December 31, 1988 | Louisville, KY | Kentucky | 75 | No. 14 Louisville | 97\n| December 30, 1989 | Lexington, KY | Kentucky | 79 | No. 8 Louisville | 86\n| December 29, 1990 | Louisville, KY | No. 18 Kentucky | 93 | Louisville | 85\n| December 28, 1991 | Lexington, KY | No. 17 Kentucky | 103 | No. 21 Louisville | 89\n| December 12, 1992 | Louisville, KY | No. 3 Kentucky | 88 | No. 9 Louisville | 68\n| November 27, 1993 | Lexington, KY | No. 2 Kentucky | 78 | No. 7 Louisville | 70\n| January 1, 1995 | Louisville, KY | No. 5 Kentucky | 86 | Louisville | 88\n| December 23, 1995 | Lexington, KY | No. 4 Kentucky | 89 | No. 25 Louisville | 66\n| December 31, 1996 | Louisville, KY | No. 3 Kentucky | 74 | No. 16 Louisville | 54\n| December 27, 1997 | Lexington, KY | No. 4 Kentucky | 76 | Louisville | 79\n| December 26, 1998 | Louisville, KY | No. 3 Kentucky | 74 | Louisville | 83\n| December 18, 1999 | Lexington, KY | Kentucky | 76 | Louisville | 46\n| January 2, 2001 | Louisville, KY | Kentucky | 64 | Louisville | 62\n| December 29, 2001 | Lexington, KY | No. 6 Kentucky | 82 | Louisville | 62\n| December 28, 2002 | Louisville, KY | No. 14 Kentucky 