las]]\n|-\n| December 28, 2019\n| [[College Basketball on CBS|CBS]]\n| [[Brad Nessler]]\n| [[Bill Raftery]]\n|-\n\n===Football===\n{{Main|Governor's Cup (Kentucky)}}\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2017}}\nThe football rivalry between Kentucky and Louisville started one year earlier than the basketball rivalry but also had a long dormant period.  Kentucky and Louisville first played each other in football in 1912. Kentucky dominated six meetings between the teams from 1912 until 1924, holding Louisville scoreless in all six games, after which the teams stopped playing. In 1994, with former Kentucky player Howard Schnellenberger coaching Louisville, the series was revived after a 70-year dormancy.  Kentucky leads the series currently 17\u201315 but Louisville leads the Governors Cup series 15-11.\n\nFrom 1994 to 2006 the annual matchup was the first game of the season for Kentucky and was the first game for all but two of those years for Louisville.  In 2007 the game was moved to the third game of the season when played in Lexington but remained the first game when played in Louisville. Starting in 2014, which marked Louisville's inaugural season in the Atlantic Coast Conference, the Governor's Cup became the last game of the regular season for both teams to coincide with several other ACC-SEC same-state rivalries.\n\nThe 2019 game was won by Kentucky 45-13.  Kentucky wide receiver Lynn Bowden Jr. was named MVP of the showdown.\n\n== Other sports ==\n\n* '''Women's basketball''': Kentucky leads the series 34\u201320 as of the 2017\u201318 season. Most recently, no. 3 Louisville beat Kentucky 87-63 in Lexington on December 17, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukathletics.com/news/2017/12/17/womens-basketball-kentucky-louisville-postgame-notes.aspx?path=wbball|title=Kentucky-Louisville Postgame Notes|publisher=University of Kentucky Athletics|accessdate=January 29, 2018|date=December 17, 2017}}</ref> Kentucky entered that game having won five of the past six meetings with Louisville.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukathletics.com/news/2017/12/15/womens-basketball-kentucky-hosts-no-3-4-louisville-sunday-in-memorial-coliseum.aspx?path=wbball|title=Kentucky Hosts No. 3/4 Louisville Sunday in Memorial Coliseum|publisher=University of Kentucky|accessdate=January 29, 2018|date=December 15, 2017}}</ref> The series dates back to the 1911\u201312 season, long before Kentucky and Louisville's programs became varsity in 1974\u201375, from which the series has been continuously active.<ref name=\"WBB series\">{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/ukathletics.com/documents/2017/11/3/2017_18_WBB_Media_Guide_Complete_FNL.pdf|title=Scores vs. All Opponents|page=153|work=Believe in Blue: 2017-18 Women's Basketball Media Guide|publisher=University of Kentucky|year=2017}}</ref>\n* '''Women's volleyball''': Most recently winning 3-0 in Lexington, Kentucky leads the series 30\u201325 as of 2018 in a series that initially was played every year from 1977 to 2005 except in 1981 and resumed in 2009 after a hiatus.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/ukathletics.com/documents/2017/8/23/Online_MEdia_GUide.pdf|pages=62-63|title=Kentucky Volleyball 2017 Media Guide|publisher=University of Kentucky|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukathletics.com/news/2017/9/15/volleyball-no-12-kentucky-wins-fifth-straight-over-louisville.aspx|title=No. 12 Kentucky Wins Fifth Straight Over Louisville|author=Moore, Deb|date=September 15, 2017|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''Men's soccer''': The two men's soccer programs have met 31 times. Kentucky leads 15\u201314\u20135. The last meeting between the two was on September 3, 2019 which ended in a 3-0 Louisville win.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wall|first1=Garrett|title=Cardinals Shut Out No. 9 Wildcats 3-0|url=http://gocards.com/news/2019/9/3/mens-soccer-cardinals-shut-out-no-9-wildcats-3-0.aspx|website=gocards.com|publisher=[[Louisville Cardinals]]|accessdate=January 21, 2018|date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Baseball''': As of 2018, Kentucky leads the series 71\u201345\u20131 in a series dating back to 1925.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/ukathletics.com/documents/2017/8/9/2017_media_guide.pdf|title=Kentucky vs. all opponents|work=2017 Kentucky Baseball Media Guide|publisher=University of Kentucky|year=2017|page=108}}</ref><ref name=\"2017 baseball\">http://ukathletics.com/schedule.aspx?schedule=37</reF> In 2017, Louisville won the season series 3\u20131, including a sweep of Kentucky in the [[2017_NCAA_Division_I_Baseball_Tournament#Louisville_Super_Regional|NCAA Tournament Louisville Super Regional]].<ref name=\"2017 baseball\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kentucky Wildcats]]\n* [[Louisville Cardinals]]\n* [[Governor's Cup (Kentucky)]]\n* [[The Rivalry: Red V. Blue]]\n* [[Local derby|Traditional athletic rivalries in many countries of the world]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Kentucky Wildcats women's basketball navbox}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals men's basketball navbox}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals women's basketball navbox}}\n{{Kentucky Wildcats men's soccer navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kentucky-Louisville rivalry}}\n[[Category:Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball]]\n[[Category:Louisville Cardinals men's basketball]]\n[[Category:College basketball rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:College soccer rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:College sports rivalries in the United States]]\n[[Category:1912 establishments in Kentucky]]\n", "name_user": "Anomalocaris", "label": "safe", "comment": "properly close table (|}); improve <ref>s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kentucky%E2%80%93Louisville_rivalry"}
